The women of L7 are the
epitome of raunch — playing
heaw, come-hither rock while
sporting tight pants with “Iips”
sewn to the crotch area. I
want to like them, really. Yet I
find that I cannot. Punk as
they are visually, their music is
just darn ordinary. Sure, it’s
kinda hard, kinda sexy, but it’s
been done before, and it
wasn’t even that good the first
time around. Hell — Poison’s
got them beat as far as sound
goes.

There’s no getting around it
— this record particularly
sucks. It took a good deal of
stamina for me just to listen to
the whole rotten, repetitive
thing. First of all, the lyrics are
incredibly stupid. Example:
“Down in North Hollywood

there’s a guy with long hair, P

and he's really, really, nice.”
That’s a direct quote from the
first song on the album,
“Andres.” Actually, “Andres” is
the most tolerable song on the
album —- almost worth a lis-
ten. Even so, it still hasn't an
ounce of originality. This
music is about as basic as it
gets — just generic rock and
roll. Plus the vocals sound all
strained, not even in some
cool Janis Joplin emotionality,
just in a lame “my voice is not
very strong or very good” sort
of way. '

The only cool thing about
this band is that it’s all female.
It's quite a shame that they're

getting publicity and big book'- ’

ings (i.e. Lollapalooza), when
there are so many other all-girl

heavy rock bands who are infi-V

nitely superior. Seven Year
Bitch would be just one exam-
ple.

So if you’re in the mood to
hear weak vocals, cheesy gui-
tar riffs and piss-poor rhymes,
or if you’re just plain Hungry
For Stink, pick this baby up
‘cause it’s definitely stinkin’.

- rebecca corrigan

Muse Sick-N-Hour Mess Age
Public Enemy .
Def Jam Recordings

Suburbian sell-outs, Feds
and white devils, dope-
smokin’ gangstas, shit-talking
media critics and most of all,
perpetrators of black-on-black
violence: step off -—— way, _way
dafucback — because PE’s
back and their black power
gospel is gonna getcha. First,
jump five years to the last day
of the 20th century and dig the
album’s premise — president
David Duke of the United
World States of EuroAmerica,
the New World Order, has

declared war on African Unity,
and Chuck D’s mission is to
protect the people by any
means necessary. The not-so-
futuristic scenario works well
to forefront problems PE has
with American society (for
example, the proliferation of
guns, gang banging, drug
dealing and the seIf-destruc-
tive indulgence in such activi-
ties) and allows Chuck, Flava
and Terminator X to dis
wacked concepts like
Columbus Day, the Star
Spangled Banner and the
Pledge of Allegiance.

On one level, the album
functions as good ole’ “911 is
a Joke” fun (“What Kind of
Power We Got?”), clap-clap
kinesis (“Give it Up” and
“Living in a Zoo Remix”),
urgent siren-infused funk,
(“WhoIe Lotta Love”) and
goofy sci-fi soul led by PE’s
hip hop hoodlum, Flava Flav
(who recently accumulated his
24th citation for driving without
a license). So, there is ample
muse-sick in this mess-age;
but closer to Chuck D’s “fuck

the 40-ounce” concerns, the
rhyme animal reemerges as a
furious activist/educator with
an entire nation to wake up.
Indeed, this lecture is as
focused as any previous
Public Enemy album — serv-
ing as precise intellectual
bombs that would make
Eldridge Cleaver proud.

Muse Sick-N-Hour Mess
Age, PE’s fifth album, is soni-
cally scattered, a shotgun blast
at a broad target audience. PE
added a reggae flavor “Thin
Line Between Law and Rape,”
placed a bit more emphasis on
‘70s blaxploitation funk, mel-
low Soul Train choruses and
even delves into spoken word
poetics laid over a montage of
old PE snippets (“They Used
to Call it Dope”). But watch out
because some stray bullets
(“What Side you On?” and
“Bedlam 13:13”) both annoy-
ingly repetitive —— and boring
— will leave gange-green
inducing shrapnel in your CD
player. In fact, “What Side You
On?” is undeniably the worst
song on the CD, with a chorus

of angry freedom fighters
demanding over and over
“What muthafuckln side you
on?” While it is not only dull
and repetitious, the song remi-
nisces mob-like terror with an
“us/good versus them/bad”
mentality, simplistically backed
by a tired bump-bumb bass
track. I

But the album redeems itself
with house-rockin soul power
on “What Kind of Power We
Got” and, using Chuckie’s ter-
minology, several “airstrikes
from the airwaves.” PE is at
their best when they return to
familiar conscious-raising terri-
tory on “Aintnuttin’ Buttersong”
(referring to “The Star
Spangled Banner” as nothing
but violent, militaristic propa-
ganda). It samples Jimi
Hendrix’s spangled riffs and
ends with PE’s own power-to-
the people interpretation of
America's flag: “The red is for
the blood that we shed/ the
blue is for those sad-assed
songs that we be singing in
church/ the stars is what we
saw when our ass got beat/

stripes is for the whip marks in
our back/ the white is for the
obvious, there ain't no black in
that flag.”

The evaluation and subse-
quent dismissal of American
icons and rituals continues on
“Hitler Day,” which parallels
Columbus Day and “Hitler
Day” as holidays of absurdity.
“Why are we, as a people,
forced to celebrate days like
Columbus Day,” the liner notes
state, “when it kicked off 500
years of genocide. That’s as
crazy as celebrating Hitler
Day.” Obviously, ideological
confrontation has remained
the driving force behind PE’s
funk and the band knew how
to deliver.

Although lacking “Fear of a
Black P|ai1et’s” relentless wail-
ing and the snide poetics from
“Nation of Millions,” the raps
do offer a semi-appealing evo-
Iution on wax. Public Enemy is
lyrical sociology, Muse Sick is
simply a cheap textbook, and
Chuck D is a damn good pro-
fessor.

- jon hayes

