The Seagull soars through a
solid three hours of sheer
Chekhov psychoanalytic feast.
The play rises over a number
of subjects such as ‘pure the-
ater,’ mocking actors as a
group and leaving a commen-
tary of what they should be,
envy of talent that can'con—
sume the soul and destructive
love.

The beautiful script buoys
the play. At times it plays con-
science, reminding the audi-
ence to keep its principles 
and its heart.

Light and dark, good and
evil, yin and yang are repre-
sented in the forms of Irina
(Jeri Misler) and Nina (Jenna
Kalinowski) who end up in love
with the same man, Boris
Alekseyevich Trigorin (Thom
Deventhal), and in doing so,
drive another (Kostantin,
played by Jeff Carpenter) to
desperate measures.

Irina, Kostantin’s mother,

cannot accept her son’s true
worth. Hell, she cannot accept
anything that doesn’t serve her
immediate gratification. Enter
Trigorin, an unhappy writer,
who allows her to dominate the
part of his life he has set aside
for the female touch. A former
actress, she uses vulgar, tact-
less outbursts to grasp her
audience’s attention, but rarely
receives its pity. She is a frag-
ile, insecure woman in the
guise of a confident socialite.
Her polar opposite, Nina,
enters the play as Kostantin’s
girlfriend, as uncaged in shar-
ing her dreams as she is with
her love. A creature of soul,
she never perceived that in
chasing her dreams she could
get burned. in all her naivete,
her innocence is created and
destroyed during the course of
the play. The audience sees
her character take flight per-
forming with the theater she
has become so caught up in.
and destroyed by the man she
most admires and is brought
closer to by this tragic art.
Every woman in this play is
in love with the wrong man.

Every man in this play hurts
the woman who loves him the
most. No one is allowed to get
off emotionally easy in this
play. Especially the audience.
This four-act confuses and
melds random acts of love.
Masha (Bryn Jameson) is in
love with Kostantin, who all but
despises her. So she marries
a teacher (Juan Rivera) who is
close to him, but whom she
doesn’t love. The reasoning
behind actions like this are
never fully explained. Chekhov
loved this narrative realism.
The sets are rough, but

\.-\

appropriate for a 19th century
Russian country estate. The
closeness the audience is
allowed in the limited space of
the Studio Theater draws them
into the character’s lives.
Jenna Kalinowski shines as
Nina. Her subtlety is startlingly
real, and her sincerity is gen-
uine. Jeri Misler’s boisterous
character is a terrific success
as Nina’s foil. Her cattiness is
just right in a part that could be
easily overdone. Thom
De|venthal’s Trigorin is decid-
edly inconstant, as he should
be, but at the end one has to

strain closer to get what his
character is really saying.
However, the supporting
actors get lost in the shuffle by
the end scene in Kostantin’s
study, and the audience is
given little chance to care
about what happens to them.
The Seagull opens Grex
Theater’s first season with a
study of the classic. Actors can
look at this as a commentary
on their art, while everyone
else can relate to it, thanks to
Chekov, as a commentary on
their lives. The Grex Theater
will perform it at the Studio

