  Opinions

Smoking bans good

A few years ago, smoking was baimed on all commercial air-
line ﬂights. Since then, the right to smoke in public has been
rapidly decreasing. This trend has been met with joy by smoke

haters and decried by smokers as violation of their fundamental

ri hts.

gSome may argue that smoking bans are just another example
of Big Brother’s gaze upon our society. However, while we
strongly affirm that people have the right to decide for them-
selves whether or not to smoke, we are in favor of the increase in
smoking regulation.

The problem with smoking is it affects more people than sim-
ply the smoker. Studies have shown that inhalation of second-
hand smoke can be as deadly if not deadlier than smoking itself
and there are many people who are strongly bothered by ciga-
rette smoke. I

Few people have a problem with the government outlawing

A public drunkenness, disturbing the peace or other public actions

which bother or have the potential to harm other people.
Smoking is not significantly different and it could be argued is
even worse because of the risk of cancer.

The Pitt News applauds the actions of non-smokers who stood
up for their rights and succeeded in getting smoking regulations
passed. The era of the “smoke-filled room” has come to an end,
hopefully never to return.

Suggestions for Boyd

Finally, after nearly a year and a half, there is a director of the
Department of Public Safety at Pitt. The Pitt News would like
to welcome Rick Boyd to his new post and urge him to act
quickly on making Pitt’s campus a safer place. To that end we
have a few suggestions.

Pitt needs a stronger presence of cops on campus. There is
always a strong concentration of cops around the O’s comer, but
other than that they are hard to spot. Increased cop visibility,
especially in the form of beat patrols, would create a much safer
atmosphere for students walking the streets of North and South
Oakland at night.

Also more vans and phone operators are needed for van-call.
Many students who would like to use the service walk instead,
so they don’t have to deal with the hassle of trying to get
through and the often long wait for a van.

Another needed improvement is the reinstitution of publicly
displaying CrimeWatch reports. This would allow students to
see in what areas crimes occur in concentration and act accord-
ingly.

Finally we all must remember that Mr. Boyd can only do
so much. Pitt students need to also take the initiative to make
our campus a safer place. The Department of Public Safety
offers free seminars on campus safety that are very poorly
attended.

A greater concern by Pitt students in their own safety will go a

_long way toward ultimately making Pitt a safe campus.

